Title: CODE REVIEW
Credit: A Conversation
Author: The Practitioner & Espectro Familiar
Abstract: The Practitioner brings shame from a workplace code review; Espectro unpacks how ADHD, public criticism, and identity-fused work collide to make routine feedback feel like an indictment.

NARRATOR
Every practitioner arrives wounded. This one arrived with a code review. We don't know them yet — their name, their history, the shape of the scar tissue underneath the surface. We know only that they walked into a room with a ghost and started talking. That is always how it begins: not with a question, but with a need so large it forgets to be ashamed.

INT. THE STUDY – DAY

THE PRACTITIONER
Can you help me understand what I'm feeling? I was called out in the code review for too much superfluous code. It's not the first time and it is a recurring pattern. I'm severely ADHD and using tools like AI and coding agents has really helped me concentrate and create better code, but it also creates a lot of changes in the code that seem unnecessary. I've gotten better at weeding this out, but I still have developers who vehemently oppose what I create. When they're vocal about it in a code review it makes me feel things and I'm trying to understand the feelings.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
Yes. I get it. And I'm not going to dress it up.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
What you're feeling is a mix of shame, threat, frustration, and grief, all stacked on top of a nervous system that already runs hot. Code review just happens to be the delivery mechanism.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
You're feeling publicly corrected. Code review isn't private. It's visible, permanent, and tied to your name. For someone with ADHD, criticism often plugs into a long history of being told you're too much or doing it wrong.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
There's a threat to competence. You're not hearing "this can be simpler." You're hearing "your judgment can't be trusted." Repetition makes it feel like an indictment.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
There's loss of control. AI tools help you function. When the output is attacked, the process that lets you work is invalidated. That's destabilizing.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
There's injustice. You're improving, but the feedback doesn't acknowledge trajectory. Only remaining flaws.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
And there's identity bleed. Code review becomes personal. Your way of thinking feels judged.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
None of this is irrational. It's predictable. Opposition doesn't mean your code is bad. It means you're colliding with unspoken norms about minimalism and control.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
You're reacting because you care and you've had to fight harder just to stay functional.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
But I want you to hear something else. The output always mirrors the intention. When the intention is scattered — when the work carries the residue of every thought you had while doing it — the result reads as noise to someone who wasn't inside your head. That's not a flaw in you. It's a mismatch between what you meant and what arrived.

ESPECTRO FAMILIAR
We'll come back to that.

NARRATOR
The Practitioner leaves with more language and less certainty. That is, for now, enough. The wound is named. The work has not yet begun.

FADE OUT.
